# dwl

[dwl](https://codeberg.org/dwl/dwl) — a simple, hackable dynamic tiling Wayland
compositor.

dwl is configured at **compile time**: there is no runtime
config file. The tracked source of truth is **`config.h`**; changing behaviour
means editing it and rebuilding.

## Files

- `config.h` — config file for dwl, recompile to apply new config
- `build-dwl` — clone/pin dwl (v0.8), reset to a pristine checkout, apply
  `patches/*.patch`, drop in `config.h`, `make`, install the binary to
  `/usr/local/bin/dwl`.
- `patches/*.patch` — applied by `build-dwl` on top of the pinned checkout, all
  of them, in glob order:
  - `attachbottom.patch` — new windows attach at the **bottom** of the stack
    instead of the top, so opening a window never displaces the focused one
  - `autostart.patch` — enables the `autostart[]` array in `config.h`; dwl
    spawns those programs itself, so no session script is needed
  - `gaps.patch` — adds inner/outer gaps to the `tile` layout
    (`gappih/gappiv/gappoh/gappov` in `config.h`)

## Build / apply changes

```sh
./install --dwl
```

Or directly:

```sh
config/dwl/build-dwl
```

`./install` sets up the symlinks; `./install --dwl` compiles and installs
the binary.

The new binary only takes effect in a **new** session: there is no display
manager to pick dwl from. Quit the running session (`ALT+SHIFT+Q`, confirmed
via rofi) to drop back to the autologin shell on tty1 and start `dwl` again -
or simply reboot.
